TY  - JOUR
AU  - Smith, Bruce D.
AU  - Stutzer, Michael
T1  - A Theory of Mutual Formation and Moral Hazard with Evidence from the History of the Insurance Industry
PY  - 1995
Y1  - 1995/04/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/8.2.545
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 8
IS  - 2
SP  - 545
EP  - 577
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Nonprofit, mutually owned insurance and banking organizations have significant market shares in the insurance and banking industries. A first step in a systematic study of these financial mutuals is to examine the reasons for their formation. Doing so provides empirical support for the view that these mutuals arose as an efficient means of addressing contracting challenges caused by aggregate uncertainties and moral hazard. A formal model with this property is presented. We argue that information asymmetries do more to explain the kinds of contracts offered by financial mutuals than do agency problems between owners, managers, and customers.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/8.2.545
ER  - 



